Today’s extended session focused on the Map interface and the use of Iterator in the Java Collections Framework. 
A Map is used to store data in key–value pairs, where each key is unique and maps to a specific value. Unlike List, 
Map does not allow duplicate keys, and unlike Set, it stores values along with keys. The mentor explained that Map is 
part of the java.util package and is widely used when data needs to be retrieved using a unique identifier.

Different implementations of Map were discussed. HashMap stores entries in an unordered format and provides fast 
performance. LinkedHashMap maintains insertion order of elements. TreeMap stores entries in sorted order based on keys. 
The performance and ordering behavior differ depending on the implementation used.

The session also covered the Iterator interface, which is used to traverse collections. Iterator provides methods 
such as hasNext() to check if more elements are present and next() to retrieve the next element. When working with Map, 
the entrySet() method is commonly used to access key–value pairs, and then an iterator is applied to traverse them.

The working flow starts by creating a Map object and adding entries using the put() method. To traverse, entrySet() 
is used to get all entries, and an iterator loops through them. The hasNext() method checks for remaining elements, 
and next() retrieves each entry. This approach allows safe and structured traversal of collections.

This concept is important because Map and Iterator are widely used for managing structured data efficiently in real-time 
applications.